                    "creatorType": "author",
                    "firstName": "M. Brock",
                    "lastName": "Fenton"
                }
            ],
            "abstractNote": "Using echolocation, bats can distinguish true targets from background clutter and find insect prey or flowers with nectar.\n          , \n            \n              Most bats use echoes of sounds they produce to locate objects in their path. Echoes from the leaves of some plants are potential distractions (clutter) for echolocating bats as they search for flying insect prey. However, in other situations, echoes from specialized leaves are beacons that guide bats to flowers bearing nectar and pollen. Two reports in this issue—by Simon\n              et al.\n              (\n              \n                1\n              \n              ) on page 631 and Bates\n              et al.\n              (\n              \n                2\n              \n              ) on page 627—substantially advance our knowledge about how echolocating bats suppress or exploit echoes as they navigate, forage, or hunt in various environments.",
